Incoming livestream: And so, yeah, some key takeaways. One is, the evals that we've seen so far, especially in academia, unfortunately don't translate well into production.


367
01:11:45.576 --> 01:12:02.295
Incoming livestream: The second thing, too, was, fine-tuning on domain-specific data sets, beats general-purpose models, by a wide, wide margin, and I think in the security industry, we should be doing more of that and open sourcing that work.


368
01:12:02.896 --> 01:12:26.386
Incoming livestream: The third thing is that, using Frontier models as your agent is a massive step up when it comes to prompt injection. They're gonna keep getting better and better, but especially the jump most recently from Opus 4.5 or GPT 5.1 to Opus 4.6 and 5.2 is a significant improvement to prompt injection security. You should please update.


369
01:12:26.936 --> 01:12:40.816
Incoming livestream: And then, yeah, defense in depth, non-negotiable. I could do a whole talk about, like, all the other things that we do, even past detection, past detection in, in Comet.


370
01:12:40.816 --> 01:12:45.625
Incoming livestream: But for now, like, even in detection, having multiple layers is super important.


371
01:12:45.626 --> 01:13:03.086
Incoming livestream: And then finally, building that data flywheel. Because like we saw in our research, new attacks, the models, even BrowseSafe, struggle with detecting brand new attacks or brand new injection techniques that we haven't seen before. And so having that flywheel is super important.


372
01:13:06.986 --> 01:13:23.415
Incoming livestream: Cool. Yeah, I want to give… first off, I want to say that both the model and the data set is fully open source. You could download it on Hugging Face. We also have shared our paper that goes super, super in-depth into what this research does and how we did it.


373
01:13:23.456 --> 01:13:41.896
