381
01:14:59.296 --> 01:15:07.195
Incoming livestream: Open sourcing, sort of an oracle that can be used to teach the bad guys what we'll get through, versus,


382
01:15:07.316 --> 01:15:08.706
Incoming livestream: You know, sort of…


383
01:15:08.766 --> 01:15:22.266
Incoming livestream: holding back your data? Yeah, that's a good question. I'm… I'm a huge fan of open sourcing our work. I just… I feel like, defenders really need


384
01:15:22.306 --> 01:15:47.245
Incoming livestream: I mean, I feel like I need, like, we need a lot of help, right, with detecting these types of attacks, and so, at the end of the day, like, these red teams, these threat actors, they're going to be poking around and trying to find these vulnerabilities anyway, and I would love for us in Perplexity, but also the rest of the security industry, to please, share more and open source more. I feel like we see a lot of these blogs


385
01:15:47.246 --> 01:15:48.886
Incoming livestream: post talking about


386
01:15:48.886 --> 01:16:08.035
Incoming livestream: all the things that XYZ product did, or how… or how, like, threat actors are using Opus to conduct attacks, but they don't actually share any IOCs or things how to protect yourself from those attackers. And so, yeah, I'm just a huge fan of open sourcing our work.


